&nbsp;
The global average temperature of the last twelve months (from May 2023 to April 2024) is the highest ever recorded, with 0.73 centigrade degrees above the average of the period 1991-2020 and 1,61 degrees above the preindustrial average of 1850-1900. El Nino in the eastern equatorial Pacific continued to weaken towards neutral conditions, but the temperatures of the marine air were generally unusually high. According to Carlo Buontempo> of Copernicus Climate Change, > while temperature variations associated with natural cycles such as El Nino go and come, "the extra energy trapped in the oceans and in the atmosphere by increasing greenhouse gas concentrations will continue to push global temperatures towards new records".
